🧪 PART 1: Create Cloud Storage Bucket & Upload Image
✅ Step 1: Open Cloud Shell
Click Activate Cloud Shell (top right)
✅ Step 2: Set Location

Choose one:

export LOCATION=ASIA
✅ Step 3: Create Bucket (Unique Name)
gcloud storage buckets create -l $LOCATION gs://$DEVSHELL_PROJECT_ID

✔️ Bucket created using your project ID

✅ Step 4: Download Image
gcloud storage cp gs://cloud-training/gcpfci/my-excellent-blog.png my-excellent-blog.png
✅ Step 5: Upload Image to Bucket
gcloud storage cp my-excellent-blog.png gs://$DEVSHELL_PROJECT_ID/
✅ Step 6: Make Image Public
gsutil acl ch -u allUsers:R gs://$DEVSHELL_PROJECT_ID/my-excellent-blog.png
🔁 Step 7: Configure Lifecycle Rule (IMPORTANT)

👉 Go to:

Cloud Storage → Buckets
Click your bucket
Go to Lifecycle → Add rule
Configure:
Condition: Age = 30 days
Action: Change storage class → Nearline

✔️ Save

🎯 Result
Object moves from Standard → Nearline after 30 days
🧪 PART 2: Create Web Server VM
✅ Step 8: Create VM

Go to Compute Engine → VM instances → Create

Configure:
Name: bloghost
Machine: e2-standard-2
OS: Debian 12
✔ Enable Allow HTTP traffic
✅ Step 9: Add Startup Script

Paste:

#!/bin/bash
apt-get install apache2 php php-mysql -y
service apache2 restart

Click Create

✅ Step 10: Note IPs
Copy External IP
Copy Internal IP
🧪 PART 3: Create Cloud SQL Database
✅ Step 11: Create SQL Instance

Go to Cloud SQL → Create Instance

Configure:
Engine: MySQL
Instance ID: blog-db
Password: Passw0rd1!
Region/Zone: same as VM
Edition: Enterprise → Sandbox
✅ Step 12: Enable Public Access
Go to Connections → Networking
Click Add Network

Enter:

Name: web-server
Network: <VM external IP>/32

Click Save

✅ Step 13: Create User
Go to Users → Add user
Username: blogdbuser
Password: Passw0rd1!
🧪 PART 4: Connect VM to Cloud SQL
✅ Step 14: SSH into VM
gcloud compute ssh bloghost
✅ Step 15: Create PHP File
cd /var/www/html
sudo nano index.php

Paste:

<html>
<body>
<h1>My Blog</h1>
<?php
$dbserver = "CLOUDSQLIP";
$dbuser = "blogdbuser";
$dbpassword = "Passw0rd1!";

try {
$conn = new PDO("mysql:host=$dbserver;dbname=mysql", $dbuser, $dbpassword);
echo "Connected successfully";
} catch(PDOException $e) {
echo "Connection failed: " . $e->getMessage();
}
?>
</body>
</html>
✅ Step 16: Replace Values
Replace CLOUDSQLIP with your SQL Public IP
✅ Step 17: Restart Apache
sudo service apache2 restart
✅ Step 18: Test

Open browser:

http://<VM-External-IP>/index.php

✔️ Output: Connected successfully

🧪 PART 5: Display Image from Cloud Storage
✅ Step 19: Get Image URL
Go to Cloud Storage → Bucket
Copy Public URL of image
✅ Step 20: Edit PHP File
sudo nano /var/www/html/index.php

Add above <h1>:

<img src='YOUR_IMAGE_URL'>
Give feedback
✅ Step 21: Restart Server
sudo service apache2 restart
✅ Step 22: Verify

Reload:

http://<VM-IP>/index.php

✔️ You will see:

Image
Blog title
Database connection message
